[[File:BigMoseleyCard.jpg|thumb|[[Henry Moseley]] in the Balliol-Trinity Laboratories in 1910.<ref name="heilbron1974">{{cite book | authorlink = John L. Heilbron | last=Heilbron | first=John L. | title=H. G. J. Moseley: The Life and Letters of an English Physicist, 1887–1915 | publisher=[[University of California Press]] | location=Berkeley & Los Angeles | year=1974 | isbn=0-520-02375-7 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vO0d-SBw6DEC&printsec=frontcover | pages=9, 27, 29, 33, 36–38, 95 | ref=harv}}</ref>]]
The '''Balliol-Trinity Laboratories''' in [[Oxford]], [[England]], was an early [[chemistry]] laboratory at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name="bowen70">{{cite journal| first=Edmund J. | last=Bowen | authorlink=E. J. Bowen | title=The Balliol-Trinity Laboratories 1853–1940| journal=[[Notes and Records of the Royal Society of London]] | volume=25 | number=2 | pages=227–236 |date=December 1970 | url=http://rsnr.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/25/2/227 }}</ref> The laboratory was located between [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol College]] and [[Trinity College, Oxford|Trinity College]], hence the name.<ref name="balliol">{{cite web| url=http://archives.balliol.ox.ac.uk/History/chemistry.asp | title=Chemistry at Balliol: History | work=Balliol College Archives & Manuscripts | publisher=[[Balliol College, Oxford]] | location=UK | accessdate=26 August 2015 }}</ref><ref name="trinity">{{cite web| url=http://www.trinity.ox.ac.uk/undergraduates/subjects/chemistry/ | title=Chemistry | publisher=[[Trinity College, Oxford]] | location=UK | accessdate=26 August 2015 }}</ref> It was especially known for [[physical chemistry]].
Chemistry was first recognized as a separate discipline at [[Oxford University]] in the 19th century. From 1855, a chemistry laboratory existed in a basement at Balliol College.<ref name="bowen70" /> In 1879, Balliol and Trinity agreed to have a laboratory at the boundary of the two colleges. The laboratory became the strongest of the Oxford college research institutions in chemistry.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=faf1nMjVRYwC&pg=PA118&lpg=PA118 | page=118 | title=Chemistry at Oxford: A History from 1600 to 2005 | first1=Robert J. P. | last1=Williams | first2=Allan | last2=Chapman |authorlink2=Allan Chapman (historian) | first3=John S. | last3=Rowlinson | publisher=[[Royal Society of Chemistry]] | ISBN=978-0854041398 | year=2009 }}</ref> It remained in operation until the [[Second World War]] when a new [[Physical Chemistry Laboratory]] (PCL) was constructed by Oxford University in the [[Science Area, Oxford|Science Area]].<ref name="bowen70" />
==People== The following scientists of note worked in the Balliol-Trinity Laboratories:
{{div col}} * [[E. J. Bowen]] * Sir [[John Conroy (chemist)|John Conroy]] * Sir [[Harold B. Hartley|Harold Hartley]] * Sir [[Cyril Norman Hinshelwood]] ([[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] winner) * [[Henry Moseley]] {{div col end}} {{expand list|date=August 2015}}
==See also== * [[Abbot's Kitchen, Oxford]], another early chemistry laboratory in Oxford * [[Department of Chemistry, University of Oxford]] * [[Physical Chemistry Laboratory]], which replaced the Balliol-Trinity Laboratories
