[[Category:Scientific terminology]]

'''Li Fan''' (Chinese: 李梵, [[Hanyu pinyin|pinyin]]: Lǐ Fàn) was a [[China|Chinese]] [[astronomer]] during the [[Han Dynasty]] (202 BC-220 AD).
He noticed that the [[Moon]] does not move uniformly through its phases by using background [[star]]s as reference.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} In 85 Li Fan and Bian Xin (Chinese: 編訢) were tasked by [[Emperor Zhang of Han|Emperor Zhang]] to resolve inaccuracies in the [[Chinese calendar#Taichu calendar and the calendars from the Han to Ming dynasties.|Taichu calendar]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=49OvCQAAQBAJ&pg=PR9#v=onepage|title=A Biographical Dictionary of Later Han to the Three Kingdoms (23-220 AD)|last=Crespigny|first=Rafe de|date=|publisher=Brill|year=2007|isbn=9789047411840|location=Leiden|pages=410|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Foundations_of_Celestial_Reckoning.html?id=IT9DjwEACAAJ|title=The Foundations of Celestial Reckoning: Three Ancient Chinese Astronomical Systems|last=Cullen|first=Christopher|date=2017|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781138101173|location=|pages=139, 377|language=en}}</ref> He is also known to have worked with [[Water clock|inflow clepsydras]] as opposed to earlier, typically less accurate outflow clepsydras.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Science_and_Civilisation_in_China_Volume.html?id=jfQ9E0u4pLAC|title=Science and Civilisation in China: Volume 3, Mathematics and the Sciences of the Heavens and the Earth|last=Needham|first=Joseph|date=1959|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=9780521058018|location=|pages=320|language=en}}</ref>
The measurements of [[Orbital period#Synodic period|synodic periods]] of the planets given in the following table are attributed to him.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Science_and_Civilisation_in_China_Volume.html?id=jfQ9E0u4pLAC|title=Science and Civilisation in China: Volume 3, Mathematics and the Sciences of the Heavens and the Earth|last=Needham|first=Joseph|date=1959|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=9780521058018|location=|pages=401|language=en}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" |+Comparison of Li Fan's values for the [[Orbital period#Synodic period|synodic periods]] of the planets<ref name=":0" /> !Planet !True value (days) !Li Fan's value (days) |- |[[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] |115.877 |115.881 |- |[[Venus]] |583.921 |584.024 |- |[[Mars]] |779.936 |779.532 |- |[[Jupiter]] |398.884 |398.846 |- |[[Saturn]] |378.092 |378.059 |} An [[Li Fan (crater)|impact crater]] that is located at the [[Phaethontis quadrangle]], [[Mars]], 47.2°S Latitude and 153.2°W Longitude was named in his honor. The diameter of the impact crater is approximately 104.8&nbsp;km.
