{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox person | name = Liz Bonnin | image = Meeting Liz Bonnin (4872753859).jpg | imagesize = | caption = Liz Bonnin in August 2010 | birth_name = Elizabeth Bonnin | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1976|9|16|df=y}}<ref name="science"/> | birth_place = [[Paris]], [[France]] | nationality = [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] | occupation = Television presenter | years_active = 2002–present | salary = | networth = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | awards = | module = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes | background = solo_singer | alias = | origin = [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] | genre = [[Pop music|Pop]] | occupation = | instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]] | years_active = | label = [[Polydor Records|Polydor]] | associated_acts = | website = | notable_instruments = }} | website = {{URL|http://www.lizbonnin.com/}} }}
'''Elizabeth Bonnin''' (born 16 September 1976)<ref>{{cite news|title=Here's the lowdown on Liz Bonnin - presenter of Galapagos on BBC1|url=https://www.thesun.co.uk/living/2278072/liz-bonnin-wild-alaska-live-galapagos-countrywise-presenter/|newspaper=The Sun|date=30 July 2017| first=Natalie|last=Keegan}}</ref> is an [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] science, wildlife and natural history presenter, who has worked on television in both Ireland and the United Kingdom.<ref name="IrishmanAbroad">{{cite podcast |authorlink=Jarlath Regan |author=Jarlath Regan|edition=61 |work=[[An Irishman Abroad]] |title=Liz Bonin |publisher=[[SoundCloud]] |date=15 November 2014 |url=https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/liz-bonnin-episode-61 |accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="biog">{{cite web|url=http://www.lizbonnin.com/about-liz|title=About Liz|website=Liz Bonnin|access-date=2016-12-08}}</ref> She is also a [[biochemist]] and Wild Animal Biologist.<ref name="gordonpoole.com">{{Cite news|url=http://www.gordonpoole.com/talent/liz-bonnin/|title=Liz Bonnin - The Gordon Poole Agency Ltd|newspaper=The Gordon Poole Agency Ltd|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-12-08}}</ref> She presented music shows ''[[RI:SE]]'' and ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' in the early 2000s.
She is best known for presenting wildlife and science programmes including ''Galapagos'', ''How the Earth Works'', ''Animals in Love'', ''[[Stargazing Live]]'', ''Big Blue Live'', ''Cats v Dogs: Which is Best?'' and ''Should We Close Our Zoos?''.<ref name="gordonpoole.com"/>
She co-presented the [[BBC]] factual series ''[[Bang Goes the Theory]]'' from 2009 until 2014 and since 2013, has co-presented ''[[Countrywise]]'' for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]].
==Early life and education== Bonnin was born in [[Paris]] to a [[Trinidad and Tobago|Trinidadian]] mother, Bonnie Murray, of Indian and Portuguese descent, and a French-[[Martiniquan]] father, Russ Tamblyn, who was a dentist.<ref name=biog/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/whats-on/find-things-to-do/liz-bonnin-dreams-living-provence-3040141|title=Why Liz Bonnin dream's of living in provence|last=|first=|date=2011-07-01|work=|newspaper=coventrytelegraph|access-date=2016-12-08|via=}}</ref> Her family moved to Ireland when she was nine years old.<ref name="IrishmanAbroad"/><ref name=biog/>
Bonnin has a bachelor's degree in [[biochemistry]] from [[Trinity College, Dublin]],<ref name="IrishmanAbroad"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/bang/the_team/about_liz.shtml|title=Meet Liz Bonnin|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref> She also holds a master's degree in Wild Animal Biology from the [[Zoological Society of London]] and the [[Royal Veterinary College]] (2008), for which she tracked [[tigers in Nepal]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Jeremy Torrance web producer |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/natureuk/2010/10/autumnwatch-ask-liz-bonnin-a-qu.shtml |title=Nature UK: Autumnwatch: Ask Liz Bonnin a question |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2010/apr/16/liz-bonnin|title=Liz Bonnin: 'I'm still a nerd, just a different type of a nerd'|first=Stuart|last=O'Connor|date=16 April 2010|work=The Guardian|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref> She continues to work on [[big cat]] conservation programmes at the [[Zoological Society of London|Zoological Society]].
==Career== [[File:Liz Bonnin sitting in meadow 2 Credit Andrew Crowley.jpg|thumb|Liz Bonnin sitting in meadow in June 2018]] Bonnin began her career by joining an Irish [[girl pop group]] named Chill, who signed to [[Polydor]] but broke up before recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbizireland.com/news/june02/14-bonnan01.shtml|title=Can Liz Bonnin RI:SE to the Occasion?|publisher=ShowBiz Ireland|date=14 June 2002}}</ref> The band had performed on [[Dustin the Turkey]]'s third album ''[[Faith of Our Feathers]]'', duetting on "[[We Are Family (song)|We Are Family]]".<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.last.fm/music/Dustin/Faith+Of+Our+Feathers |title=Dustin-Faith of our Feathers track list |publisher=[[Last.fm]] |accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> She was offered a job hosting the [[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA Awards]] which led to presenting roles on [[RTÉ Television]] in Ireland, on ''[[The Den (Ireland)|The Den]]'', ''[[Telly Bingo]]'', ''[[Millennium Eve: Celebrate 2000]]'' and for two years, ''[[Off the Rails (TV series)|Off the Rails]]'' with Fiona McShane.<ref name="IrishmanAbroad"/> At the time she was in a relationship with the publisher John Ryan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/olaf-bares-all-1.1117909|title=Olaf bares all|last=|first=|date=25 November 2000|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2017-04-03|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hotpress.com/features/interviews/John-Ryan/416453.html|title=John Ryan Interview|last=Jackson|first=Joe|date=14 September 2000|website=Hot Press Magazine|language=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-03}}</ref> In 2002 she moved to London to present on a number of TV channels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/tv/ttv/thecafe//bonnindarcy.html|title=Liz Bonnin and Gordon D'Arcy|publisher=[[RTÉ]]|accessdate=14 April 2008}}</ref>
In 2002 she became one of the presenters of the [[Channel 4]] morning show ''[[RI:SE]]'', specialising in reporting on entertainment-related stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/liz-bonnin/person/132317/summary.html|title=Liz Bonnin|publisher=[[TV.com]]|accessdate=14 April 2008}}</ref> In the same year she became a regular presenter on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/totp2/trivia/presenters/|title=Top of the Pops 2 – Trivia|publisher=BBC|accessdate=14 April 2008}}</ref>
In 2004 Bonnin was locked in a giant kennel along with MPs [[Paul Burstow]], [[Evan Harris]] and [[Ivan Henderson]] and actress [[Liza Goddard]], [[BBC]] ''[[Newsround]]'' presenter [[Lizzie Greenwood]] and DJ [[Becky Jago]] in a stunt to launch the annual [[RSPCA]] Week to raise awareness and funds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3659185.stm|title=MPs in the doghouse for charity|publisher=BBC|date=26 April 2004}}</ref>
Since 2005 Bonnin has been involved in science broadcasting. She presented the show ''Gadgets, Gadgets, Gadgets'' in 2005<ref>{{IMDb title|0493379|Gadgets, Gadgets, Gadgets}}</ref> and co-presented the BBC science series ''[[Bang Goes the Theory]]'' on [[BBC One]] from 2009 until 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8079912.stm|title=Talking Shop:Liz Bonnin|publisher=BBC|date=3 June 2009}}</ref> In 2008, Bonnin presented a documentary series ''Science Friction'' on [[RTÉ One]] which looked at taboos in discussions of scientific topics (such as [[paedophilia]] and [[nuclear power]]) in Ireland.<ref name="IrishmanAbroad"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rte.ie/presspack/2008/02/04/science-friction-new-series/ |title=SCIENCE FRICTION ***New Series*** |publisher=[[RTÉ]] Press Centre |date=4 February 2008 |accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> She also contributed to [[BBC Two]]'s series on the work of the London [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]], ''[[Museum of Life (film)|Museum of Life]]''.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/11_november/11/historyandreligion.shtml|title=Museum of Life|publisher=BBC|date=11 November 2009}}</ref>
In October 2010 she joined the cast of ''[[Autumnwatch]]'' and in January 2011, she presented segments of [[BBC Two]]'s ''[[Stargazing Live]]'' from various areas of Hawaii including atop [[Mauna Kea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spew.co.uk/blog/2011/01/06/stargazing-live-tv-gold/|title=Stargazing Live: TV Gold|publisher=Spew.co.uk|date=6 January 2011}}</ref> In May 2011, she co-presented [[BBC One]]'s ''Egypt's Lost Cities''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b011pwms|title=Egypt's Lost Cities|date=31 May 2011}}</ref>
==Personal life== Bonnin grew up with her older sister Benni, while she said that "I was extremely close to my granny, who passed away in 2003."{{cn|date=July 2018}} She has moved back to London and said in 2015, "It's a big culture shock when I come back to London after a month away in somewhere like [[Botswana]]. I love walking in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]] or [[Kensington Gardens]] just to look at the trees and breathe a little before adjusting to life back in the big city."{{cn|date=July 2018}}
Bonnin is a role model for [[EDF Energy]]'s Pretty Curious programme, which is aimed at encouraging teenage girls to study science-based subjects at school.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mccarthy |first=Fiona |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-3406401/Emotional-ties-BBC-wildlife-presenter-Liz-Bonnin.html |title=Emotional ties with BBC wildlife presenter Liz Bonnin |website=Dailymail.co.uk |date=2016-01-23 |accessdate=2016-12-09}}{{better source|date=July 2018}}</ref> She has said in a 2016 interview, "[[FHM]] offered me a spread but I said no."<ref name="science">{{cite web|author=John Meagher Twitter Email |url=http://www.independent.ie/style/celebrity/celebrity-features/former-rte-star-liz-bonnin-on-choosing-science-over-celebrity-fhm-offered-me-a-spread-but-i-said-no-34704999.html |title=Former RTE star Liz Bonnin on choosing science over celebrity: 'FHM offered me a spread but I said no' |website=Independent.ie |date=2016-05-15 |accessdate=2016-12-09}}</ref>
