{{chemistry-stub}}

'''Sham feeding''' is any procedure that mimics normal food consumption but where food and drink are not actually digested or absorbed. It is generally used in experiments studying hunger, eating or digestion, and is a predominant method used in studying [[binge eating disorder]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Corwin |first=Rebecca L |last2=Buda-Levin |first2=Ariel |date=2004 |title=Behavioral models of binge-type eating |journal=[[Physiology & Behavior]] |publisher= |volume=82 |issue=1 |pages=123–130 |doi=10.1016/j.physbeh.2004.04.036}}</ref> In [[animal research]] it often involves inserting a tube into either the [[oesophagus]] or stomach, that leaks out anything that has been swallowed.<ref name=kalat>{{cite book |last=Kalat |first=James W |date=2013 |title=Biological Psychology, 11th edition |publisher=[[Cengage Learning|Wadsworth]] |page=302 |isbn=978-1-111-83952-9}}</ref> Animals who are sham fed in this manner eat and swallow almost continually without becoming satiated.<ref name=kalat/> [[Chewing gum]] can also be considered sham feeding,<ref name=daily/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Fitzgerald |first=Edward F. |last2=Ahmed |first2=Irfan |date=September 10, 2009 |title=Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis of Chewing-Gum Therapy in the Reduction of Postoperative Paralytic Ileus Following Gastrointestinal Surgery |url= |journal=World Journal of Surgery |publisher= |volume=33 |issue=12 |pages=2557–66 |doi= 10.1007/s00268-009-0104-5 |pmid=19763686}}</ref> as whilst very-little or no nutrients are being absorbed into the body, the process of chewing still stimulates digestive system nerves which trigger the release of gastrointestinal hormones, and also increase the production of both saliva and pancreatic secretions.<ref name=daily>{{cite web |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2008/08/080818183936.htm |title=Chewing Gum Associated With Enhanced Bowel Recovery After Colon Surgery |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date=August 19, 2008 |work=[[Science Daily]] |publisher= |accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> In human studies a process known as modified sham feeding (MSF) is typically used, which involves smelling, tasting and chewing food, then spitting it out when it would normally be swallowed.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Robertson |first=Denise M |date=2001 |title=Prolonged effects of modified sham feeding on energy substrate mobilization |url=http://ajcn.nutrition.org/content/73/1/111.long |journal=[[The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition]] |publisher= |volume=73 |issue=1 |pages=111–117 |doi= |accessdate=7 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Arosio |first=Maura |date=2004 |title=Effects of modified sham feeding on ghrelin levels in healthy human subjects |url=http://press.endocrine.org/doi/full/10.1210/jc.2003-032222 |journal=[[The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology and Metabolism]] |publisher= |volume=89 |issue=10 |pages=5101–5104 |doi= 10.1210/jc.2003-032222|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref>

